attributes.title: Smiling versus Neutral Face
attributes.description: Do participants like another person more when the person being evaluated is smiling versus when they are making a neutral face?

q1.value: Participants' preference on images of a person smiling versus a person making a neutral face

q3.value: The purpose of this study is to examine whether people like a person they are evaluating more when they are smiling versus when they are making a neutral face.

q4.value: I hypothesize that social attraction wil be higher for people who are smiling versus making a neutral face.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: Participants will be shown two pictures and will be asked whether they prefer the individual who is smiling versus making a neutral face.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: We will randomly select students on the SMU campus to take our survey. The goal is to obtain 50 males and 50 females so that every sex is equally represented. Participants under the age of 18 will be excluded from our study.

q13.value: We will obtain 100 participants from our survey. Each member of our group will get 10 males and 10 females so that every sex is equally represented.

question.value: We will measure demographic information, a self-report on attachment to their mothers, the region in which they grew up in, and the social attraction sub scale of the Interpersonal Attraction Scale (McCoskey & McCain, 1974).

I will compare whether participants choose the image of the individual making a smiling face versus a neutral face. I will also examine whether the region of their hometown and their self-report attachment to their mothers have an effect on their answer choice.

q22.value: We will exclude participants who are under the age of 18.
